<i>♪ Bend ♪♪</i>

284
00:15:16.120 --> 00:15:18.640
[purring]

285
00:15:18.720 --> 00:15:20.480
[chirping, twittering]

286
00:15:20.520 --> 00:15:22.560
[hooting]

287
00:15:30.400 --> 00:15:32.520
[old woman]
Is that my Pocahontas?

288
00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:36.640
Grandmother Willow,
I need to talk to you.

289
00:15:38.640 --> 00:15:41.280
Good morning, child.

290
00:15:41.320 --> 00:15:43.720
I was hoping
you'd visit today.

291
00:15:44.640 --> 00:15:47.240
Why, your mother's necklace!

292
00:15:47.320 --> 00:15:50.000
That's what I wanted
to talk to you about.

293
00:15:50.080 --> 00:15:52.200
My father wants me
to marry Kocoum.

294
00:15:52.280 --> 00:15:55.680
Kocoum?
But he's so serious!

295
00:15:55.760 --> 00:15:59.600
I know. My father thinks
it's the right path for me.

296
00:15:59.680 --> 00:16:02.680
But lately, I've been
having this dream,
and I think it's...

297
00:16:02.760 --> 00:16:07.200
Oh, a dream!
Let's hear all about it!

298
00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:08.680
[twittering, squeaking]

299
00:16:08.760 --> 00:16:10.360
Quiet!

300
00:16:11.800 --> 00:16:13.320
[shouting] Quiet!

301
00:16:13.360 --> 00:16:14.480
[ribbits]

302
00:16:15.520 --> 00:16:16.800
[gulping]

303
00:16:19.120 --> 00:16:21.200
Now, child,
you were saying?

304
00:16:21.280 --> 00:16:23.720
Well, I'm running
through the woods,

305
00:16:23.800 --> 00:16:26.560
and then right there
in front of me is an arrow.

306
00:16:26.640 --> 00:16:29.200
As I look at it,
it starts to spin.

307
00:16:29.280 --> 00:16:33.040
A spinning arrow?
How unusual!

308
00:16:33.080 --> 00:16:36.480
Yes, it spins faster
and faster and faster...

309
00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:38.360
until, suddenly, it stops.

310
00:16:38.400 --> 00:16:40.360
[chittering]

311
00:16:40.720 --> 00:16:42.360
Hmm.

312
00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:47.640
Well, it seems to me this
spinning arrow is pointing
you down your path.

313
00:16:47.720 --> 00:16:51.040
But, Grandmother Willow,
what is my path?

314
00:16:51.120 --> 00:16:52.720
How am I ever
going to find it?

315
00:16:52.760 --> 00:16:57.520
[chuckles]
Your mother asked me
the very same question.

316
00:16:57.560 --> 00:17:00.080
She did?
What did you tell her?

317
00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:03.080
I told her to listen.

318
00:17:03.120 --> 00:17:06.080
All around you
are spirits, child.

319
00:17:06.120 --> 00:17:11.120
They live in the earth,
the water, the sky.

320
00:17:11.200 --> 00:17:15.120
If you listen,
they will guide you.

321
00:17:18.240 --> 00:17:20.720
I hear the wind.
Yes.

322
00:17:20.760 --> 00:17:23.240
What is it
telling you?

323
00:17:23.280 --> 00:17:25.440
I don't understand.
[distant howling]

324
00:17:25.440 --> 00:17:29.080
<i>♪ Que que na-to-ra ♪</i>

325
00:17:29.120 --> 00:17:32.520
<i>♪ You will understand ♪</i>

326
00:17:32.600 --> 00:17:36.120
<i>♪ Listen with your heart ♪</i>

327
00:17:36.240 --> 00:17:40.160
<i>♪ You will understand ♪</i>

328
00:17:40.240 --> 00:17:46.160
<i>♪ Let it break upon you</i>
<i>like a wave upon the sand ♪</i>

329
00:17:46.240 --> 00:17:48.280
It's saying
something's coming.

330
00:17:48.360 --> 00:17:50.120
Strange clouds?

331
00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:53.400
<i>♪ Listen with your heart ♪</i>

332
00:17:53.440 --> 00:17:57.480
<i>♪ You will understand ♪♪</i>

333
00:17:57.560 --> 00:18:00.240
[drumming]

334
00:18:00.280 --> 00:18:01.600
[squealing]

335
00:18:01.600 --> 00:18:03.200
[purring]

336
00:18:04.240 --> 00:18:05.640
What do you see?

337
00:18:06.480 --> 00:18:10.440
Clouds. Strange clouds.

338
00:18:13.520 --> 00:18:19.320
[Ratcliffe] Look at it,
Wiggins, an entire New World
chock-full of gold,

339
00:18:19.400 --> 00:18:21.480
just waiting for me.

340
00:18:21.520 --> 00:18:25.680
And scores of adventures
waiting for us, right, Percy?

341
00:18:25.760 --> 00:18:27.640
Do you think we'll
meet some savages?

342
00:18:27.720 --> 00:18:30.720
If we do, we shall
be sure to give them
a proper English greeting.

343
00:18:30.800 --> 00:18:32.640
Oh! Gift baskets!

344
00:18:34.280 --> 00:18:36.400
And he came
so highly recommended.

345
00:18:39.240 --> 00:18:42.760
It's perfect, the water's
deep enough. We can pull
right up to shore.

346
00:18:42.840 --> 00:18:44.400
Hey, there, Percy.

347
00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.520
Very well, then.
Give the order.
Already done, sir.

348
00:18:48.560 --> 00:18:50.640
I've got a crew assembled,
and they're ready to go.

349
00:18:50.680 --> 00:18:52.520
About the natives...

350
00:18:52.600 --> 00:18:55.160
I'm counting on you
to make sure those
filthy heathens

351
00:18:55.280 --> 00:18:56.720
don't disrupt
our mission.

352
00:18:56.800 --> 00:18:59.680
Well, if they're anything
like the savages
I've fought before,

353
00:18:59.760 --> 00:19:01.320
it's nothing
I can't handle.

354
00:19:01.360 --> 00:19:04.440
Right.
That'll be all, Smith.
There's a good man.

355
00:19:04.520 --> 00:19:06.840
See ya, Percy.
[growling]

356
00:19:09.440 --> 00:19:10.840
The men like Smith,
don't they?

357
00:19:10.880 --> 00:19:12.880
[growling]

358
00:19:12.880 --> 00:19:17.360
I've never been
a popular man.
I like you.

359
00:19:17.440 --> 00:19:21.360
Don't think I don't know
what those backstabbers
at court say about me.

360
00:19:21.440 --> 00:19:23.880
Oh, yes, all that talk
about being a pathetic
social climber

361
00:19:23.960 --> 00:19:25.040
who's failed
at everything...

362
00:19:25.120 --> 00:19:26.640
I'm very well aware
that this is

363
00:19:26.720 --> 00:19:30.240
my last chance for glory.
But mark my words, Wiggins,

364
00:19:30.320 --> 00:19:32.920
when King James sees the gold
these peasants unearth,

365
00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:36.720
success will be mine,
at last.

366
00:19:38.720 --> 00:19:40.880
[man] Wake up! Shake a leg!
Two of you up
on the yardarm!

367
00:19:40.960 --> 00:19:42.640
It's incredible.

368
00:19:42.720 --> 00:19:46.240
And it's all ours.
I've never seen
anything like it.

369
00:19:46.320 --> 00:19:48.480
It can look like
Ratcliffe's knickers
for all I care,

370
00:19:48.560 --> 00:19:51.440
just as long as
I get off this
stinking boat!

371
00:19:51.520 --> 00:19:54.800
Come on, men.
We didn't come all this
way just to look at it.

372
00:19:54.880 --> 00:19:58.720
[men call]
[birds chirp]

373
00:20:01.520 --> 00:20:05.520
[wilderness sounds]

374
00:20:49.640 --> 00:20:53.920
[man] Keep it taut, lads.
Keep it taut! Steady!
Steady!

375
00:20:53.960 --> 00:20:55.800
[man 2] Hold up!
That's far enough!

376
00:20:55.880 --> 00:20:58.440
All right now...
tie her off!

377
00:20:58.480 --> 00:21:00.320
Here, John,
tie off this end.

378
00:21:00.360 --> 00:21:02.720
John? John?

379
00:21:03.960 --> 00:21:05.480
What are you
doing up there?

380
00:21:05.560 --> 00:21:06.920
Getting a better look.

381
00:21:20.400 --> 00:21:24.360
[squeaking]
[gasping]

382
00:21:24.440 --> 00:21:25.920
[purring]

383
00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:29.960
[squeaking]
[purring]

384
00:21:32.360 --> 00:21:33.640
Hey!

385
00:21:34.480 --> 00:21:35.800
[chittering]

386
00:21:35.840 --> 00:21:37.000
[gasping]

387
00:21:37.040 --> 00:21:38.760
[cooing]

388
00:21:38.840 --> 00:21:42.840
Well... you're
a strange looking fellow.

389
00:21:42.920 --> 00:21:44.600
You hungry?

390
00:21:44.680 --> 00:21:46.920
Here you go.
It's a biscuit.

391
00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:49.680
It's food.
Well, sort of.

392
00:21:51.520 --> 00:21:53.520
You like it, eh?
[purring]

393
00:21:53.600 --> 00:21:56.440
Well, try eating it
for four months straight.

394
00:21:59.480 --> 00:22:01.960
[chittering]
You got a friend
back there?

395
00:22:12.960 --> 00:22:16.000
[angry squeaking]
Hey... what the...
What...? Watch out.

396
00:22:17.720 --> 00:22:19.440
No... get that...
Look out!
[purring, chirping]

397
00:22:19.520 --> 00:22:21.720
[trumpet sounds]
John, you better
get down here!

398
00:22:21.760 --> 00:22:23.560
The governor's
coming ashore.

399
00:22:23.600 --> 00:22:25.640
[angry squeaking]
All right. I'm leaving.

400
00:22:27.040 --> 00:22:28.600
[chirping]

401
00:22:41.520 --> 00:22:42.560
[murmuring]

402
00:22:42.600 --> 00:22:43.880
[man] Did you see
their skin?

403
00:22:43.920 --> 00:22:44.960
[man 2]
Pale and sickly.

404
00:22:45.040 --> 00:22:46.560
They have hair
on their faces
like dogs.

405
00:22:46.640 --> 00:22:50.880
My brothers, we must know
more about these visitors.

406
00:22:50.920 --> 00:22:53.880
Kekata, what do you see?

407
00:22:53.920 --> 00:22:56.080
[chanting]

408
00:23:00.600 --> 00:23:05.440
[speaking Algonquian]

409
00:23:05.520 --> 00:23:10.440
[rattling, howling]

410
00:23:10.520 --> 00:23:13.600
These are not
men like us...

411
00:23:13.680 --> 00:23:18.640
...but strange beasts
with bodies that shine
like the sun,

412
00:23:18.720 --> 00:23:22.800
and weapons that
spout fire and thunder.

413
00:23:26.800 --> 00:23:30.600
They prowl the earth
like ravenous wolves,

414
00:23:30.640 --> 00:23:33.880
consuming everything
in their path.

415
00:23:38.600 --> 00:23:42.480
Great Powhatan, I will lead
our warriors to the river
and attack.

416
00:23:42.520 --> 00:23:46.480
We will destroy
these invaders the way we
destroyed the Massawomecks.

417
00:23:46.560 --> 00:23:49.880
Kocoum, in that battle
we knew how to fight
our enemy,

418
00:23:49.960 --> 00:23:52.560
but these pale visitors
are strange to us.

419
00:23:52.640 --> 00:23:54.960
Take some men
to the river
to observe them.

420
00:23:55.040 --> 00:23:57.760
Let us hope
they do not
intend to stay.

421
00:23:57.800 --> 00:23:58.880
[military drumroll]

422
00:23:58.960 --> 00:24:02.720
I hereby claim this land
and all its riches

423
00:24:02.800 --> 00:24:05.120
in the name of His Majesty,
King James the First,

424
00:24:05.160 --> 00:24:09.680
and do so name this
settlement Jamestown.

425
00:24:09.760 --> 00:24:13.840
[men cheer]
Bravo! Bravo!
Beautifully spoken, sir!

426
00:24:13.880 --> 00:24:15.160
Hurry now, Percy.

427
00:24:15.240 --> 00:24:18.000
We must be all
squeaky clean
for the New World.

428
00:24:18.080 --> 00:24:20.000
[sighing]

429
00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:24.000
[gulping]

430
00:24:24.080 --> 00:24:25.240
[purring]

431
00:24:29.600 --> 00:24:31.000
[growling]

432
00:24:31.080 --> 00:24:32.640
[purring]

433
00:24:32.680 --> 00:24:35.960
[snarling]

434
00:24:39.680 --> 00:24:40.840
[yelping]

435
00:24:42.840 --> 00:24:45.000
[purring]

436
00:24:45.040 --> 00:24:46.800
[gulping]

437
00:24:46.880 --> 00:24:48.960
[snarling]

438
00:24:49.040 --> 00:24:51.200
[barking]

439
00:24:51.240 --> 00:24:53.240
[yipping]

440
00:24:56.200 --> 00:25:00.840
[growling, moaning]

441
00:25:00.880 --> 00:25:04.880
Captain Smith,
it appears I've selected
the perfect location.

442
00:25:04.960 --> 00:25:06.200
Not a savage in sight.

443
00:25:06.240 --> 00:25:09.040
Just because we don't
see them doesn't mean
they're not out there.

444
00:25:09.880 --> 00:25:15.240
Then perhaps you should
venture forth and determine
their whereabouts, hm?

445
00:25:15.320 --> 00:25:17.880
If there are any Indians
out there, I'll find them.

446
00:25:20.920 --> 00:25:22.720
Now, gentlemen, to work.

447
00:25:22.800 --> 00:25:25.640
You men,
get the ship unloaded,
you men build the fort.

448
00:25:25.720 --> 00:25:28.680
The rest of you...
break out the shovels!

449
00:25:28.720 --> 00:25:31.600
It's time to
start digging!
Digging?

450
00:25:31.680 --> 00:25:34.920
Well, of course!
Let's not forget
what the Spanish found

451
00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:37.080
when they came
to the New World.

452
00:25:37.120 --> 00:25:40.080
Gold! Mountains of it.

453
00:25:40.160 --> 00:25:43.880
Why, for years,
they've been ravaging
the New World

454
00:25:43.920 --> 00:25:45.880
