precious resources.

455
00:25:45.920 --> 00:25:47.800
But now...

456
00:25:49.760 --> 00:25:52.240
...it's our turn.

457
00:25:52.320 --> 00:25:54.760
<i>♪ The gold of Cortez ♪</i>
[gasping]

458
00:25:54.800 --> 00:25:56.280
<i>♪ The jewels of Pizarro ♪</i>

459
00:25:56.360 --> 00:26:00.600
<i>♪ Will seem</i>
<i>like mere trinkets</i>
<i>by this time tomorrow ♪</i>

460
00:26:00.680 --> 00:26:04.240
<i>♪ The gold we find here</i>
<i>will dwarf them by far ♪</i>

461
00:26:04.280 --> 00:26:07.560
<i>♪ Oh, with all you got</i>
<i>in ya, boys ♪</i>

462
00:26:07.600 --> 00:26:11.320
<i>♪ Dig up Virginia, boys ♪</i>

463
00:26:11.400 --> 00:26:13.120
<i>♪ Mine, boys ♪</i>

464
00:26:13.200 --> 00:26:14.720
<i>♪ Mine every mountain ♪</i>

465
00:26:14.800 --> 00:26:16.240
<i>♪ And dig, boys ♪</i>

466
00:26:16.280 --> 00:26:18.000
<i>♪ Dig till ya drop ♪</i>

467
00:26:18.080 --> 00:26:19.960
<i>♪ Grab a pick, boys ♪</i>

468
00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:21.800
<i>♪ Quick, boys ♪</i>

469
00:26:21.840 --> 00:26:23.240
<i>♪ Shove in a shovel ♪</i>

470
00:26:23.280 --> 00:26:27.680
<i>♪ Uncover those</i>
<i>lovely pebbles that</i>
<i>sparkle and shine ♪</i>

471
00:26:27.760 --> 00:26:30.120
<i>♪ It's gold ♪</i>

472
00:26:30.200 --> 00:26:34.680
<i>♪ And it's mine,</i>
<i>mine, mine ♪</i>

473
00:26:34.760 --> 00:26:36.960
<i>♪ Dig and diggety dig ♪</i>

474
00:26:37.040 --> 00:26:39.640
<i>♪ And dig and dig</i>
<i>and diggety dig ♪</i>

475
00:26:39.720 --> 00:26:42.800
<i>♪ Hey, nonny, nonny hi,</i>
<i>nonny, nonny ♪</i>
<i>♪ Ooh, how I love it ♪</i>

476
00:26:42.840 --> 00:26:45.880
<i>♪ Hey, nonny, nonny hi,</i>
<i>nonny, nonny ♪</i>
<i>♪ Riches for cheap ♪</i>

477
00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:49.080
<i>♪ Hey, nonny, nonny hi,</i>
<i>nonny, nonny ♪</i>
<i>♪ There'll be heaps of it ♪</i>

478
00:26:49.160 --> 00:26:52.000
<i>♪ And I'll be</i>
<i>on top of the heap ♪</i>

479
00:26:52.040 --> 00:26:54.000
<i>♪ Diggety, diggety,</i>
<i>diggety, dig! ♪</i>

480
00:26:54.040 --> 00:26:57.200
<i>♪ My rivals back home</i>
<i>it's not that I'm bitter ♪</i>

481
00:26:57.280 --> 00:27:00.880
<i>♪ But think how they'll squirm</i>
<i>when they see how I glitter ♪</i>

482
00:27:00.960 --> 00:27:04.080
<i>♪ The ladies at court</i>
<i>will be all a-twitter ♪</i>

483
00:27:04.160 --> 00:27:06.160
[sighing]
<i>♪ The king will reward me ♪</i>

484
00:27:06.200 --> 00:27:09.840
<i>♪ He'll knight me</i>
<i>No! Lord me ♪</i>

485
00:27:09.920 --> 00:27:13.920
<i>♪ It's mine!</i>
<i>Mine, mine for the taking ♪</i>

486
00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:16.800
<i>♪ It's mine, boys</i>
<i>Mine me that gold ♪</i>

487
00:27:16.840 --> 00:27:21.800
<i>♪ With those nuggets dug</i>
<i>it's glory they'll give me ♪</i>

488
00:27:21.840 --> 00:27:26.280
<i>♪ My dear friend,</i>
<i>King Jimmy will probably</i>
<i>build me a shrine ♪</i>

489
00:27:26.360 --> 00:27:30.040
<i>♪ When all of the gold ♪</i>

490
00:27:30.080 --> 00:27:31.400
<i>♪ Is mine ♪</i>

491
00:27:31.480 --> 00:27:34.160
<i>♪ And dig and dig</i>
<i>and diggety dig ♪</i>

492
00:27:34.200 --> 00:27:37.080
<i>♪ And dig and dig</i>
<i>and diggety dig ♪</i>

493
00:27:37.160 --> 00:27:41.040
<i>♪ All of my life I have</i>
<i>searched for a land</i>
<i>like this one ♪</i>

494
00:27:43.360 --> 00:27:47.720
<i>♪ A wild or more challenging</i>
<i>country I couldn't design ♪</i>

495
00:27:50.200 --> 00:27:54.920
<i>♪ Hundreds of dangers await</i>
<i>and I don't plan to miss one ♪</i>

496
00:27:56.800 --> 00:28:00.080
<i>♪ In a land I can claim,</i>
<i>a land I can tame ♪</i>

497
00:28:00.160 --> 00:28:03.680
<i>♪ The greatest</i>
<i>adventure is mine ♪</i>
<i>♪ Keep on working, lads ♪</i>

498
00:28:03.720 --> 00:28:05.400
<i>♪ Mine ♪</i>
<i>♪ Don't be shirking, lads ♪</i>

499
00:28:05.480 --> 00:28:08.440
<i>♪ Mine, boys, mine ♪</i>

500
00:28:08.520 --> 00:28:13.960
<i>♪ Mine me that gold ♪</i>

501
00:28:14.040 --> 00:28:16.720
<i>♪ Beautiful gold ♪</i>
<i>♪ Dig for that gold ♪</i>

502
00:28:16.800 --> 00:28:20.720
<i>♪ Make this island my land ♪</i>

503
00:28:20.800 --> 00:28:23.920
<i>♪ Make the mounds big, boys</i>
<i>I'd help you to dig, boys ♪</i>

504
00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:26.080
<i>♪ But I've got this</i>
<i>crick in me spine ♪</i>

505
00:28:26.160 --> 00:28:29.720
<i>♪ This land we behold ♪</i>
<i>♪ This beauty untold ♪</i>

506
00:28:29.760 --> 00:28:34.080
<i>♪ A man can be bold ♪</i>
<i>♪ It all can be sold ♪</i>

507
00:28:34.160 --> 00:28:36.040
<i>♪ So go for the gold ♪</i>

508
00:28:36.080 --> 00:28:37.720
<i>♪ We know which is here ♪</i>

509
00:28:37.760 --> 00:28:43.520
<i>♪ Mine, mine, mine ♪♪</i>
[indistinct singing]

510
00:28:50.160 --> 00:28:52.120
[rushing water]

511
00:30:03.360 --> 00:30:04.960
[purring]

512
00:31:31.600 --> 00:31:34.280
No! Wait! Please...

513
00:31:42.520 --> 00:31:44.120
Please!

514
00:31:46.320 --> 00:31:48.080
Don't run off.

515
00:31:51.120 --> 00:31:54.000
It's all right.
I'm not going to hurt you.

516
00:31:55.280 --> 00:31:57.440
Here. Let me help you
out of there.

517
00:31:57.520 --> 00:32:00.960
[speaking Algonquian]

518
00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:03.360
You don't understand a word
I'm saying, do you?

519
00:32:08.600 --> 00:32:10.160
It's all right.

520
00:32:27.520 --> 00:32:31.280
<i>♪ Listen with your heart ♪</i>

521
00:32:31.320 --> 00:32:34.640
<i>♪ You will understand ♪</i>

522
00:32:38.240 --> 00:32:39.680
[squeaking]

523
00:32:42.160 --> 00:32:44.960
<i>♪ Let it break upon you ♪</i>

524
00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:49.360
<i>♪ Like a wave</i>
<i>upon the sand ♪</i>

525
00:32:50.600 --> 00:32:52.160
Who are you?

526
00:32:52.280 --> 00:32:56.000
<i>♪ Listen with your heart ♪</i>

527
00:32:56.080 --> 00:33:01.080
<i>♪ You will understand ♪♪</i>

528
00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:03.400
Pocahontas.

529
00:33:03.480 --> 00:33:06.080
What? What did you say?

530
00:33:06.160 --> 00:33:09.520
My name is Pocahontas.

531
00:33:13.760 --> 00:33:15.360
I'm John Smith.

532
00:33:20.560 --> 00:33:22.600
That's it.
Keep at it, men.
[men grunt]

533
00:33:22.680 --> 00:33:25.560
Keep digging.
It's got to be
here somewhere.

534
00:33:27.560 --> 00:33:29.840
There's 30 more
down by the ridge.

535
00:33:29.880 --> 00:33:31.160
That makes
more than 100!

536
00:33:31.200 --> 00:33:32.520
Anything yet?

537
00:33:32.560 --> 00:33:34.720
Nothing but rocks
and dirt, sir.

538
00:33:34.800 --> 00:33:38.680
How long are we going to
keep digging like this, sir?

539
00:33:38.720 --> 00:33:41.400
We're slaving away,
busting our backs
day and night...

540
00:33:41.440 --> 00:33:44.080
For king and country.
I know, I know.

541
00:33:44.160 --> 00:33:47.160
And I share your fatigue.
Wiggins!

542
00:33:47.600 --> 00:33:48.800
Wiggins!

543
00:33:50.400 --> 00:33:53.280
Coming!
Dispose of this.

544
00:33:53.360 --> 00:33:57.560
[whimpering]
Who's a good doggie?

545
00:33:57.600 --> 00:33:59.320
Who's a good doggie?
[sighing]

546
00:33:59.840 --> 00:34:01.640
Fetch, boy!

547
00:34:05.800 --> 00:34:07.760
[yelping]
Savages! It's an ambush!

548
00:34:07.840 --> 00:34:10.240
Arm yourselves!
Run!

549
00:34:10.320 --> 00:34:13.280
Arm yourselves!
[men shout]

550
00:34:13.280 --> 00:34:15.800
Make sure every man
has a musket!

551
00:34:16.600 --> 00:34:17.640
Shoot!

552
00:34:20.520 --> 00:34:22.760
Them, you idiot!

553
00:34:27.640 --> 00:34:30.320
[yipping]

554
00:34:33.640 --> 00:34:36.440
Where's that blasted Smith
when I need him?

555
00:34:39.600 --> 00:34:41.800
[blast]

556
00:34:41.840 --> 00:34:43.280
[groaning]

557
00:34:43.360 --> 00:34:44.440
Namontack!

558
00:34:45.640 --> 00:34:50.560
[grunting, groaning]

559
00:34:55.800 --> 00:34:57.360
Back to the village!

560
00:34:57.920 --> 00:34:59.840
[cheering]

561
00:34:59.920 --> 00:35:04.520
Shut up. Shut up, you fools!
They'll be back.

562
00:35:05.840 --> 00:35:07.480
Everyone back to camp.

563
00:35:07.520 --> 00:35:10.160
Get the rest of the cannons
ashore, finish building the
fort!

564
00:35:10.240 --> 00:35:12.400
Aye, Governor!

565
00:35:12.480 --> 00:35:17.160
And you... learn to use
that thing properly.

566
00:35:17.200 --> 00:35:21.160
A man's not a man
unless he knows
how to shoot.

567
00:35:22.360 --> 00:35:25.680
[Kekata chanting]

568
00:35:25.760 --> 00:35:28.840
[groaning]
[rattling, chanting]

569
00:35:28.920 --> 00:35:33.360
These beasts
invade our shores,
and now this.

570
00:35:33.480 --> 00:35:35.880
[rattling, chanting]

571
00:35:35.960 --> 00:35:38.600
This wound is
strange to me.

572
00:35:38.680 --> 00:35:41.680
[groans]

573
00:35:41.760 --> 00:35:45.640
We will fight this enemy,
but we cannot do it alone.

574
00:35:45.680 --> 00:35:48.880
Kocoum, send messengers to
every village in our nation.

575
00:35:48.960 --> 00:35:51.800
We will call on
our brothers
to help us fight.

576
00:35:51.840 --> 00:35:54.800
These white men
are dangerous!

577
00:35:54.880 --> 00:35:57.520
No one is to
go near them.

578
00:36:01.560 --> 00:36:03.160
[John]
It's called a helmet.

579
00:36:03.200 --> 00:36:05.640
[Pocahontas] Helmet.

580
00:36:05.720 --> 00:36:09.520
[squeaking]
[John] So...
what river is this?

581
00:36:09.560 --> 00:36:11.280
[Pocahontas]
Quiyoughcohannock.

582
00:36:11.360 --> 00:36:14.200
You have the most
unusual names here.

583
00:36:14.280 --> 00:36:17.760
Chickahominy. Quiyo...
Quiyoughcohannock.

584
00:36:18.800 --> 00:36:21.200
Pocahontas.

585
00:36:21.200 --> 00:36:24.640
You have the most
unusual name, too.

586
00:36:24.720 --> 00:36:27.240
John Smith.
[munching]

587
00:36:27.320 --> 00:36:31.760
Hey! Is this bottomless pit
a friend of yours?

588
00:36:31.840 --> 00:36:33.760
Meeko!

589
00:36:33.840 --> 00:36:35.520
Well, how do you do, Meeko?

590
00:36:36.720 --> 00:36:38.640
[purring]

591
00:36:38.720 --> 00:36:41.800
It's all right.
It's just a handshake.

592
00:36:41.880 --> 00:36:43.720
Here, let me show you.

593
00:36:45.600 --> 00:36:46.920
Nothing's happening.

594
00:36:46.960 --> 00:36:49.840
No, no.
I need your hand first.

595
00:36:54.760 --> 00:36:56.880
It's how we say hello.

596
00:36:59.440 --> 00:37:00.760
[purring, squeaking]

597
00:37:00.800 --> 00:37:04.480
This is how we say hello.
<i>Winggapo.</i>

598
00:37:07.760 --> 00:37:10.480
<i>Winggapo.</i>

599
00:37:10.560 --> 00:37:14.520
And how we say
goodbye. <i>Anah.</i>

600
00:37:14.600 --> 00:37:17.360
I like hello better.

601
00:37:18.600 --> 00:37:20.880
[squeaking]

602
00:37:20.960 --> 00:37:22.560
[angry chirping]

603
00:37:22.600 --> 00:37:24.440
Yeah, I remember you.

604
00:37:25.720 --> 00:37:27.960
Flit just doesn't
like strangers.

605
00:37:28.040 --> 00:37:29.840
But I'm not a stranger
anymore.

606
00:37:29.920 --> 00:37:32.560
Hmm. Stubborn little fellow,
isn't he?

607
00:37:32.640 --> 00:37:34.560
Very stubborn.
[blows raspberry]

608
00:37:34.640 --> 00:37:35.680
Hey!

609
00:37:37.040 --> 00:37:39.280
Meeko! Come back here.

610
00:37:39.400 --> 00:37:41.280
Don't worry.
He can't hurt it.

611
00:37:41.360 --> 00:37:43.080
Hey! What are you doing?

612
00:37:43.120 --> 00:37:44.480
Meeko, bring that back.

613
00:37:44.560 --> 00:37:46.800
No, it's all right.
He can keep it.

614
00:37:46.840 --> 00:37:48.400
Call it a gift.

615
00:37:49.480 --> 00:37:50.760
[clanging]

616
00:37:50.800 --> 00:37:52.320
What was that?

617
00:37:52.400 --> 00:37:54.280
My compass.
Compass?

618
00:37:54.320 --> 00:37:56.360
It tells you how to find
your way when you get lost.

619
00:37:56.440 --> 00:37:58.600
It's all right.
I'll get another in London.

620
00:37:58.640 --> 00:38:00.480
London?
Is that your village?

621
00:38:00.560 --> 00:38:02.480
Yes.
It's a very big village.

622
00:38:02.560 --> 00:38:03.640
What's it like?

623
00:38:03.680 --> 00:38:06.920
It's got streets
filled with carriages,

624
00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:10.920
bridges over the rivers,
and buildings
as tall as trees.

625
00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:13.320
I'd like to see
those things.
You will.

626
00:38:13.360 --> 00:38:14.920
How?
We're going to
build them here.

627
00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:18.320
We'll show your people
how to use this land
properly.

628
00:38:18.400 --> 00:38:19.480
How to make
the most of it.

629
00:38:19.520 --> 00:38:20.760
Make the most of it?

630
00:38:20.840 --> 00:38:23.880
Yes. We'll build roads
and decent houses...

631
00:38:23.960 --> 00:38:25.920
Our houses are fine.

632
00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:28.800
You think that
only because you
don't know any better.

633
00:38:30.680 --> 00:38:32.520
Wait a minute.
Don't take it that...

634
00:38:32.560 --> 00:38:35.680
Hey! Wait!
[squeaking]

635
00:38:35.760 --> 00:38:39.480
Wait! There's so much
we can teach you.

636
00:38:39.520 --> 00:38:41.520
We've improved the lives
of savages all over
the world.

637
00:38:41.600 --> 00:38:43.360
Savages?

638
00:38:43.440 --> 00:38:44.960
Not that
you're a savage.

639
00:38:45.040 --> 00:38:46.720
Just my people.
No.

640
00:38:46.800 --> 00:38:49.760
Listen, that's not what
I meant. Let me explain.

641
00:38:49.840 --> 00:38:53.000
Let go!
No. I'm not
letting you leave.

642
00:38:54.880 --> 00:38:56.560
Look, don't do this.

643
00:38:56.600 --> 00:39:00.040
Savage is just a word,
you know?

644
00:39:00.080 --> 00:39:03.880
A term for...
people who are uncivilized.

645
00:39:03.920 --> 00:39:05.040
Like me.

646
00:39:05.080 --> 00:39:09.400
Well, when I say
uncivilized,
what I mean is...

647
00:39:09.480 --> 00:39:10.800
[snapping, yelling]

648
00:39:10.880 --> 00:39:12.800
[moaning]

649
00:39:12.880 --> 00:39:14.880
[clanging, grunting]

650
00:39:18.720 --> 00:39:22.400
What you mean is...
not like you.

651
00:39:22.480 --> 00:39:25.640
<i>♪ You think</i>
<i>I'm an ignorant savage ♪</i>

652
00:39:25.760 --> 00:39:28.080
<i>♪ And you've been</i>
<i>so many places ♪</i>

653
00:39:28.120 --> 00:39:30.560
<i>♪ I guess it must be so ♪</i>

654
00:39:30.640 --> 00:39:33.120
<i>♪ But still, I cannot see ♪</i>

655
00:39:33.200 --> 00:39:36.640
<i>♪ If the savage one is me ♪</i>

656
00:39:36.720 --> 00:39:41.600
<i>♪ How can there be so much</i>
<i>that you don't know ♪</i>

657
00:39:43.040 --> 00:39:47.640
<i>♪ You don't know ♪</i>

658
00:39:55.680 --> 00:40:00.640
<i>♪ You think you own</i>
<i>whatever land you land on ♪</i>

659
00:40:00.720 --> 00:40:05.120
<i>♪ The earth is just</i>
<i>a dead thing you can claim ♪</i>

660
00:40:05.160 --> 00:40:09.680
<i>♪ But I know every rock</i>
<i>and tree and creature ♪</i>

661
00:40:09.800 --> 00:40:14.440
<i>♪ Has a life, has a spirit,</i>
<i>has a name ♪</i>

662
00:40:14.480 --> 00:40:17.800
<i>♪ You think the only people</i>
<i>who are people ♪</i>

663
00:40:17.840 --> 00:40:18.920
[growling]

664
00:40:18.960 --> 00:40:20.120
<i>♪ Are the people ♪</i>

665
00:40:20.160 --> 00:40:23.120
<i>♪ Who look</i>
<i>and think like you ♪</i>

666
00:40:23.160 --> 00:40:27.520
<i>♪ But if you walk</i>
<i>the footsteps of a stranger ♪</i>

667
00:40:27.600 --> 00:40:32.160
<i>♪ You'll learn things</i>
<i>you never knew</i>
<i>you never knew ♪</i>

668
00:40:32.280 --> 00:40:37.200
<i>♪ Have you ever heard the wolf</i>
<i>cry to the blue corn moon? ♪</i>

669
00:40:37.280 --> 00:40:41.480
<i>♪ Or ask the grinning bobcat</i>
<i>why he grinned? ♪</i>

670
00:40:41.560 --> 00:40:46.200
<i>♪ Can you sing with all</i>
<i>the voices of the mountain? ♪</i>

671
00:40:46.280 --> 00:40:50.960
<i>♪ Can you paint with all</i>
<i>the colors of the wind? ♪</i>

672
00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:54.760
<i>♪ Can you paint</i>
<i>with all the colors ♪</i>

673
00:40:54.840 --> 00:40:58.280
<i>♪ Of the wind? ♪</i>

674
00:41:05.280 --> 00:41:09.200
<i>♪ Come run the hidden pine</i>
<i>trails of the forest ♪</i>

675
00:41:09.280 --> 00:41:13.640
<i>♪ Come taste the sun-sweet</i>
<i>berries of the earth ♪</i>

676
00:41:13.680 --> 00:41:17.600
<i>♪ Come roll in all the riches</i>
<i>all around you ♪</i>

677
00:41:17.680 --> 00:41:22.040
<i>♪ And for once, never wonder</i>
<i>what they're worth ♪</i>

678
00:41:22.120 --> 00:41:26.200
<i>♪ The rainstorm and the river</i>
<i>are my brothers ♪</i>

679
00:41:26.280 --> 00:41:30.960
<i>♪ The heron and the otter</i>
<i>are my friends ♪</i>

680
00:41:31.040 --> 00:41:34.960
<i>♪ And we are all connected</i>
<i>to each other ♪</i>

681
00:41:35.040 --> 00:41:39.960
<i>♪ In a circle,</i>
<i>in a hoop, that never ends ♪</i>

682
00:41:40.040 --> 00:41:44.240
<i>♪ How high</i>
<i>does the sycamore grow? ♪</i>

683
00:41:44.320 --> 00:41:48.920
<i>♪ If you cut it down</i>
<i>then you'll never know ♪</i>

684
00:41:50.800 --> 00:41:56.720
<i>♪ And you'll never</i>
<i>hear the wolf cry</i>
<i>to the blue corn moon ♪</i>

685
00:41:56.800 --> 00:42:00.800
<i>♪ For whether we are</i>
<i>white or copper-skinned ♪</i>

686
00:42:00.880 --> 00:42:05.600
<i>♪ We need to sing with all</i>
<i>the voices of the mountain ♪</i>

687
00:42:05.680 --> 00:42:10.600
<i>♪ We need to paint with all</i>
<i>the colors of the wind ♪</i>

688
00:42:10.680 --> 00:42:13.560
<i>♪ You can own the earth,</i>
<i>and still ♪</i>

689
00:42:13.640 --> 00:42:17.160
<i>♪ All you'll own</i>
<i>is earth until ♪</i>

690
00:42:17.240 --> 00:42:19.760
<i>♪ You can paint ♪</i>

691
00:42:19.800 --> 00:42:22.840
<i>♪ With all the colors ♪</i>

692
00:42:22.920 --> 00:42:26.760
<i>♪ Of the ♪</i>

693
00:42:26.840 --> 00:42:32.840
<i>♪ Wind ♪♪</i>

694
00:42:40.920 --> 00:42:44.160
[rustling]

695
00:42:44.240 --> 00:42:47.600
[faint drumming]

696
00:42:47.640 --> 00:42:49.240
What is it?

697
00:42:49.280 --> 00:42:52.920
The drums.
They mean trouble.

698
00:42:52.960 --> 00:42:55.760
I shouldn't be here.

699
00:42:55.800 --> 00:42:57.680
I want to
see you again.
I can't.

700
00:42:57.800 --> 00:42:59.800
Please, don't leave.
I'm sorry.

701
00:43:02.960 --> 00:43:05.000
I have to go.

702
00:43:13.280 --> 00:43:15.160
[rolling thunder]

703
00:43:15.280 --> 00:43:17.720
[man] All right!
This one's ready to hoist!

704
00:43:17.800 --> 00:43:20.200
[man 2] Two on each side.
Ready now? Push!

705
00:43:20.280 --> 00:43:22.000
Watch it!
It's slipping.

706
00:43:22.080 --> 00:43:25.160
Come on, lads,
it's only a little
picket fence.

707
00:43:25.200 --> 00:43:27.600
[man 2] Steady! Steady!
[man] There you go.

708
00:43:27.640 --> 00:43:30.000
That'll keep everything out,
eh, John?

709
00:43:32.160 --> 00:43:34.640
Something wrong, John?
What?

710
00:43:34.720 --> 00:43:36.320
You've been quiet
the last few days.

711
00:43:36.400 --> 00:43:39.760
He's mad he missed
all the action.

712
00:43:39.840 --> 00:43:42.640
Don't worry, John.
You'll get your chance
to deal with the Indians.

713
00:43:42.680 --> 00:43:46.200
Yeah. We'll take care
of them, like we did
last time, eh, mates?

714
00:43:46.280 --> 00:43:48.920
<i>♪ We shot ourselves</i>
<i>an injun ♪</i>

715
00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:50.840
<i>♪ Or maybe two or three ♪♪</i>

716
00:43:50.880 --> 00:43:53.360
All right,
you howling nutter,
get to work.

717
00:43:53.440 --> 00:43:55.960
Come on, Ben.
It's just a little fun.

718
00:43:56.000 --> 00:43:59.080
Sure! We're having
loads of fun, right?

719
00:43:59.200 --> 00:44:01.080
Look at us.
No gold, no food,

720
00:44:01.200 --> 00:44:05.480
while Ratcliffe sits up
in his tent all day,
happy as a clam.

721
00:44:06.320 --> 00:44:08.120
I'm doomed!

722
00:44:08.200 --> 00:44:10.320
I should be wallowing
in riches by now,

723
00:44:10.360 --> 00:44:12.200
and I haven't found
as much as a speck.

724
00:44:12.240 --> 00:44:17.080
Think. Think!
It's got to be
around here somewhere.

725
00:44:18.360 --> 00:44:21.360
Where could it be?
[music box plays]

726
00:44:21.440 --> 00:44:27.000
I've mined the forests and
the hills and the swamps...
and nothing!

727
00:44:27.040 --> 00:44:28.720
[growling]
[purring]

728
00:44:28.800 --> 00:44:29.880
[barking]

729
00:44:29.920 --> 00:44:33.160
Why can't I find it?
What am I overlooking?

730
00:44:33.200 --> 00:44:38.800
[groaning] I... I...
I made it myself!

731
00:44:38.880 --> 00:44:40.440
Take that silly...

732
00:44:41.360 --> 00:44:43.720
Of course. The Indians.

733
00:44:43.800 --> 00:44:47.240
Wiggins, why do you think
those insolent heathens
attacked us?

734
00:44:47.320 --> 00:44:50.720
We invaded their land,
cut down their trees
and dug up their earth?

735
00:44:50.800 --> 00:44:53.080
It's the gold!
They have it,

736
00:44:53.160 --> 00:44:55.400
and they don't want us
to take it from them.

737
00:44:55.440 --> 00:44:59.080
Well, I'll just have to
take it by force then,
won't I?

738
00:45:01.080 --> 00:45:04.040
You there!
Where's Captain Smith?

739
00:45:04.080 --> 00:45:06.240
Well, he's... gone.

740
00:45:06.280 --> 00:45:08.760
Aye. Your singing
scared him off.

741
00:45:08.840 --> 00:45:10.480
Go get him,
for heaven's sake!

742
00:45:10.600 --> 00:45:12.160
What if we run
into the Indians?

743
00:45:12.240 --> 00:45:15.160
That's what guns are for.

744
00:45:15.240 --> 00:45:17.280
Now arm yourselves
and get moving!

745
00:45:17.400 --> 00:45:19.720
[wolf howls]

746
00:45:19.760 --> 00:45:22.080
[barking]

747
00:45:25.960 --> 00:45:28.840
[chewing noisily]

748
00:45:33.080 --> 00:45:34.320
[purring]

749
00:45:34.400 --> 00:45:35.960
[groaning]

750
00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:38.800
[squeaking]

751
00:45:41.120 --> 00:45:42.800
[sighing deeply]

752
00:45:42.880 --> 00:45:44.560
[Powhatan]
Pocahontas.

753
00:45:45.520 --> 00:45:47.800
You should be inside
the village.

754
00:45:47.880 --> 00:45:49.240
We'll be all right.

755
00:45:49.280 --> 00:45:52.480
We're gathering food for
when the warriors arrive.

756
00:45:52.560 --> 00:45:54.120
Don't go far.

757
00:45:54.200 --> 00:45:55.840
Now is not the time
to be running off.

758
00:45:55.920 --> 00:45:57.160
Yes, Father.

759
00:45:58.800 --> 00:46:02.960
When I see you wear
that necklace, you look
just like your mother.

760
00:46:03.880 --> 00:46:05.440
I miss her.

761
00:46:05.480 --> 00:46:07.840
But she is
still with us.

762
00:46:07.920 --> 00:46:12.200
Whenever the wind
moves through the trees,
I feel her presence.

763
00:46:12.280 --> 00:46:15.120
Our people look to her
for wisdom and strength.

764
00:46:15.160 --> 00:46:17.960
Someday, they will
look to you as well.

765
00:46:18.000 --> 00:46:19.480
I would be
honored by that.

766
00:46:20.560 --> 00:46:22.480
You shouldn't be
out here alone.

767
00:46:22.560 --> 00:46:24.840
I'll send for Kocoum.

768
00:46:24.880 --> 00:46:26.160
All right,
what is it?

769
00:46:26.200 --> 00:46:27.840
What?
You're hiding something.

770
00:46:27.920 --> 00:46:29.840
I'm not hiding anything.

771
00:46:29.920 --> 00:46:32.000
Pocahontas, you can tell me.
I promise.

772
00:46:32.040 --> 00:46:36.080
I won't tell anyone...
Pocahontas, look!

773
00:46:36.160 --> 00:46:37.240
[buzzing]

774
00:46:39.440 --> 00:46:41.280
It's one of them!
I'm going to get...

775
00:46:41.360 --> 00:46:43.120
What are you
doing here?

776
00:46:43.160 --> 00:46:45.200
I had to see you again.
[muffled yelp]

777
00:46:45.200 --> 00:46:48.160
[Kocoum] Pocahontas!
Pocahontas!
[muffled gasp]

778
00:46:48.280 --> 00:46:50.280
Please!
Don't say anything.

779
00:46:50.360 --> 00:46:51.840
Quick! This way!

780
00:46:51.920 --> 00:46:53.480
But...
Nakoma.

781
00:46:53.520 --> 00:46:56.040
Where is Pocahontas?

782
00:46:56.120 --> 00:46:58.080
I haven't seen her.

783
00:46:59.200 --> 00:47:01.320
Pocahontas can't
keep running off.

784
00:47:01.360 --> 00:47:03.160
It's dangerous out there.

785
00:47:03.200 --> 00:47:06.280
Tell her that.
She listens to you.

786
00:47:08.560 --> 00:47:10.840
[scoffs] Sure she does.

787
00:47:10.880 --> 00:47:12.200
[squeaking]

788
00:47:21.520 --> 00:47:23.880
[munching]

789
00:47:26.600 --> 00:47:28.880
[John] This place
is incredible.

790
00:47:28.960 --> 00:47:32.160
And to think we came
all this way just to
dig it up for gold.

791
00:47:32.240 --> 00:47:34.080
[Pocahontas] Gold?
Hey, Meeko.

792
00:47:34.160 --> 00:47:35.680
What's gold?

793
00:47:35.720 --> 00:47:38.080
You know, it's yellow.

794
00:47:38.120 --> 00:47:40.240
It comes out of the ground.
It's really valuable.

795
00:47:40.320 --> 00:47:42.120
Oh! Here,
we have lots of it.

796
00:47:43.080 --> 00:47:44.440
Gold.

797
00:47:44.520 --> 00:47:48.920
No, no! Gold is this.

798
00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:51.080
There's nothing like that
around here.

799
00:47:51.120 --> 00:47:53.600
No gold?
Not that I've seen.

800
00:47:53.680 --> 00:47:56.480
[chuckling]
All this way for nothing.

801
00:47:56.560 --> 00:47:59.320
Those boys are in
for a big surprise.

802
00:47:59.440 --> 00:48:01.600
Will they leave?
Some of them might.

803
00:48:04.080 --> 00:48:05.280
Will you go home?

804
00:48:05.400 --> 00:48:08.880
Well, it's not like
I have much of a home
to go back to.

805
00:48:08.920 --> 00:48:11.360
I've never really
belonged anywhere.

806
00:48:11.440 --> 00:48:13.560
You could belong here.

807
00:48:14.280 --> 00:48:17.120
[wind singing]

808
00:48:23.040 --> 00:48:24.280
What was that?

809
00:48:24.360 --> 00:48:25.840
Did you see something?

810
00:48:25.920 --> 00:48:28.600
No, no. I just...

811
00:48:28.640 --> 00:48:31.680
I didn't see anything.
Did I?

812
00:48:31.760 --> 00:48:33.440
Look again.

813
00:48:34.640 --> 00:48:37.520
<i>♪ Let it break upon you ♪</i>

814
00:48:37.640 --> 00:48:42.320
<i>♪ Like a wave</i>
<i>upon the sand ♪♪</i>

815
00:48:43.960 --> 00:48:46.200
Hello, John Smith.

816
00:48:46.320 --> 00:48:49.200
Pocahontas, that tree
is talking to me.

817
00:48:49.320 --> 00:48:51.320
Then you should talk back.

818
00:48:51.400 --> 00:48:53.360
Don't be frightened,
young man.

819
00:48:53.440 --> 00:48:56.080
My bark is worse
than my bite.

820
00:48:57.640 --> 00:48:59.320
Say something.

821
00:48:59.360 --> 00:49:01.200
What do you say to a tree?

822
00:49:01.280 --> 00:49:03.600
Anything you want.

823
00:49:06.720 --> 00:49:08.480
So...

824
00:49:08.520 --> 00:49:11.000
Come closer, John Smith.

825
00:49:12.200 --> 00:49:16.480
He has a good soul.
And he's handsome, too!

826
00:49:16.560 --> 00:49:18.320
Oh, I like her.

827
00:49:18.360 --> 00:49:19.960
I knew you would.

828
00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:23.440
Smith! Smith,
where are you, mate?

829
00:49:23.520 --> 00:49:24.840
We can't let them
see us.

830
00:49:24.920 --> 00:49:26.160
Quick! Over here.

831
00:49:26.200 --> 00:49:30.040
This place gives me
the creeps. Savages
could be hiding anywhere.

832
00:49:30.120 --> 00:49:33.880
If you spot one,
don't ask questions.
Just shoot.

833
00:49:35.200 --> 00:49:36.320
[grunting]

834
00:49:36.360 --> 00:49:38.240
Watch your feet,
you big oaf!

835
00:49:38.320 --> 00:49:40.160
It wasn't me!
It was the tree.

836
00:49:40.200 --> 00:49:43.600
Of course!
The tree just felt
like lifting its roots...

837
00:49:46.800 --> 00:49:48.440
Let's get out of here.

838
00:49:50.120 --> 00:49:51.560
[both] Ow!
Run!

839
00:49:51.640 --> 00:49:53.360
But what about Smith?

840
00:49:53.440 --> 00:49:56.040
He's a big lad,
he can take care
of himself!

841
00:49:56.120 --> 00:49:57.360
I'm glad
you're on our side.

842
00:49:57.440 --> 00:50:00.400
There's still some snap
in these old vines.

843
00:50:00.480 --> 00:50:03.280
I better get back before
they send the whole camp
after me.

844
00:50:03.360 --> 00:50:05.080
When will I
see you again?

845
00:50:05.160 --> 00:50:07.200
Meet me tonight, right here.

846
00:50:12.400 --> 00:50:17.200
Well! I haven't had
this much excitement
in 200 years.

847
00:50:17.240 --> 00:50:20.360
What am I doing?
I shouldn't be
seeing him again.

848
00:50:20.400 --> 00:50:22.360
I mean, I want to
see him again.

849
00:50:22.400 --> 00:50:25.440
Who wouldn't?
I want to see him again.

850
00:50:25.520 --> 00:50:29.440
But, still, something
inside is telling me
it's the right thing.

851
00:50:29.520 --> 00:50:31.240
Perhaps it's your dream.

852
00:50:31.280 --> 00:50:36.360
My dream? Do you think
he's the one the spinning
arrow was pointing to?

853
00:50:36.400 --> 00:50:38.240
Hmm.

854
00:50:45.440 --> 00:50:47.240
The warriors are here.

855
00:50:52.520 --> 00:50:54.160
[chattering]

856
00:50:58.760 --> 00:51:01.600
Pocahontas, are you crazy?
What were you doing
with one of them?

857
00:51:01.680 --> 00:51:03.360
There you are!
Kocoum!

858
00:51:03.440 --> 00:51:07.320
Look at them! Now we have
enough warriors to destroy
those white demons!

859
00:51:09.320 --> 00:51:13.560
Now that we are
joined by our brothers,
we will defeat this enemy.

860
00:51:21.320 --> 00:51:23.080
Father, I need to
speak with you.

861
00:51:23.120 --> 00:51:25.680
Not now, my daughter.
The council is gathering.

862
00:51:25.760 --> 00:51:29.280
We don't have to fight them.
There must be a better way.

863
00:51:29.320 --> 00:51:32.120
Sometimes our paths
are chosen for us.

864
00:51:32.160 --> 00:51:34.680
But maybe we should try
talking to them.

865
00:51:34.760 --> 00:51:36.440
They do not
want to talk.

866
00:51:36.480 --> 00:51:38.440
But if one of them
did want to talk,

867
00:51:38.480 --> 00:51:40.240
you would listen to him,
wouldn't you?

868
00:51:40.320 --> 00:51:42.320
Pocahontas...
Wouldn't you?

869
00:51:42.360 --> 00:51:46.560
Of course I would,
but it is not that simple.

870
00:51:46.640 --> 00:51:49.240
Nothing is
simple anymore.

871
00:51:56.240 --> 00:51:57.680
[twigs snap]

872
00:51:57.800 --> 00:52:00.320
[whimpering]

873
00:52:00.360 --> 00:52:02.440
[barking]

874
00:52:03.480 --> 00:52:05.240
[growling]
[chittering]

875
00:52:12.520 --> 00:52:14.160
[barking, growling]

876
00:52:14.240 --> 00:52:16.480
[purring]

877
00:52:17.360 --> 00:52:19.520
[howling]

878
00:52:21.760 --> 00:52:23.280
[coyote howls]

879
00:52:32.120 --> 00:52:33.360
[gasping]

880
00:52:33.440 --> 00:52:36.320
Easy, Thomas, it's me.

881
00:52:36.360 --> 00:52:38.920
Oh, John!
I could've killed you.

882
00:52:39.000 --> 00:52:40.880
Not aiming like that,
you couldn't.

883
00:52:40.920 --> 00:52:43.960
Keep both eyes open
when you shoot.
You'll see twice as well.

884
00:52:45.720 --> 00:52:47.280
Smith! There you are.

885
00:52:47.360 --> 00:52:48.920
We were looking
all over for you.

886
00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:52.400
Smith! Where have you been?

887
00:52:52.400 --> 00:52:54.920
I was out scouting
the terrain, sir.

888
00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:57.560
Excellent.
Then you must know
the Indians' whereabouts.

889
00:52:57.640 --> 00:52:59.640
We'll need that
information for
the battle.

890
00:52:59.720 --> 00:53:02.160
What battle?
We will eliminate
these savages

891
00:53:02.240 --> 00:53:03.560
once and for all.

892
00:53:03.640 --> 00:53:05.840
No! You can't do that!

893
00:53:05.880 --> 00:53:07.880
Oh, can't I?

894
00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:10.560
Look. We don't
have to fight them.

895
00:53:10.640 --> 00:53:12.600
John, what's
gotten into you?
I met one of them.

896
00:53:12.680 --> 00:53:14.880
You what?
A savage?

897
00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:17.760
They're not savages.
They can help us.

898
00:53:17.880 --> 00:53:21.800
They know the land.
They know how to
navigate the rivers.

899
00:53:21.880 --> 00:53:24.560
And look. It's food.
What is it?

900
00:53:24.640 --> 00:53:26.800
It's better than hardtack
and gruel, that's for sure.

901
00:53:26.880 --> 00:53:27.920
I like gruel.

902
00:53:28.000 --> 00:53:30.720
They don't want to feed us,
you ninnies!

903
00:53:30.760 --> 00:53:33.240
They want to kill us!
All of us!

904
00:53:33.320 --> 00:53:36.400
They've got our gold,
and they'll do anything
to keep it!

905
00:53:36.440 --> 00:53:38.400
But there is no gold.

906
00:53:38.440 --> 00:53:39.720
No gold?

907
00:53:40.600 --> 00:53:44.280
And I suppose your
little Indian friend
told you this?

908
00:53:44.360 --> 00:53:45.680
Yes.

909
00:53:45.760 --> 00:53:49.480
Lies. Lies! All of it!
Murderous thieves.

910
00:53:49.560 --> 00:53:51.640
There's no room
for their kind in
civilized society.

911
00:53:51.720 --> 00:53:53.240
But this is their land!

912
00:53:53.280 --> 00:53:56.560
This is my land!
I make the laws here.

913
00:53:56.600 --> 00:54:00.840
And I say anyone
who so much as
looks at an Indian

914
00:54:00.920 --> 00:54:06.360
without killing him
on sight will be tried
for treason and hanged.

915
00:54:08.440 --> 00:54:11.280
[coyotes howl]
[panting]

916
00:54:11.320 --> 00:54:12.720
[Nakoma] Pocahontas!

917
00:54:12.800 --> 00:54:14.600
Nakoma.
Don't go out there.

918
00:54:14.640 --> 00:54:17.920
I lied for you once,
don't ask me to do it again.

919
00:54:17.960 --> 00:54:19.600
I have to do this.

920
00:54:19.640 --> 00:54:21.760
He's one of them!
You don't know him.

921
00:54:21.800 --> 00:54:24.720
If you go out there,
you'll be turning your
back on your own people.

922
00:54:24.800 --> 00:54:27.320
I'm trying to
help my people.

923
00:54:27.360 --> 00:54:30.520
Pocahontas, please,
you're my best friend.

924
00:54:30.600 --> 00:54:32.360
I don't want you
to get hurt.

925
00:54:32.440 --> 00:54:34.560
I won't.
I know what I'm doing.

926
00:54:34.640 --> 00:54:36.320
Pocahontas, no!

927
00:54:42.840 --> 00:54:45.760
[Ben] Ratcliffe wouldn't
take us halfway around
the world for nothing.

928
00:54:45.840 --> 00:54:49.320
[man] But what if Smith
is right? What if there
is no gold?

929
00:54:49.360 --> 00:54:52.560
If you ask me,
Ratcliffe's been lying
to us since we left London.

930
00:54:52.640 --> 00:54:54.560
Listen to you,
you bunch of idiots.

931
00:54:54.640 --> 00:54:56.960
Those savages didn't
attack us for nothing.

932
00:54:57.000 --> 00:54:58.760
They're
hiding something.

933
00:54:58.840 --> 00:55:02.360
If they do have the gold,
I reckon we'll have
to fight them.

934
00:55:02.440 --> 00:55:04.880
Not me. I'm not
risking my neck...
Either too hot or too cold.

935
00:55:04.960 --> 00:55:07.560
I haven't been comfortable
since we got here.

936
00:55:08.680 --> 00:55:11.120
[man] Me, too.
I'm itching a lot.

937
00:55:16.440 --> 00:55:18.080
[gasping]

938
00:55:18.160 --> 00:55:20.720
Follow him.
Yes, Governor.

939
00:55:20.800 --> 00:55:23.320
I want to know where
he's sneaking off to.

940
00:55:23.360 --> 00:55:26.360
Yes, sir.
If you happen to
see any Indians...

941
00:55:27.360 --> 00:55:28.800
...shoot them.

942
00:55:32.560 --> 00:55:35.360
Oh, and, Thomas,
you've been
a slipshod sailor

943
00:55:35.400 --> 00:55:37.800
and a poor excuse
for a soldier.

944
00:55:37.880 --> 00:55:40.080
Don't disappoint me again.

945
00:55:50.640 --> 00:55:52.320
Kocoum.
What is it?

946
00:55:53.480 --> 00:55:54.720
It's Pocahontas.

947
00:55:54.800 --> 00:55:57.080
What's wrong?
Is she all right?

948
00:55:59.120 --> 00:56:01.080
I think she's in trouble.

949
00:56:05.760 --> 00:56:08.840
The earth is
trembling, child.
What's happened?

950
00:56:08.920 --> 00:56:10.400
The warriors are here.

951
00:56:10.480 --> 00:56:13.600
Pocahontas.
John!

952
00:56:13.640 --> 00:56:17.520
Listen to me.
My men are planning
to attack your people.

953
00:56:17.600 --> 00:56:18.640
You've got to warn them.

954
00:56:18.720 --> 00:56:20.880
Maybe it's not too late
to stop this.

955
00:56:20.920 --> 00:56:23.040
You have to come with me
and talk to my father.

956
00:56:23.080 --> 00:56:25.800
Pocahontas, talking
isn't going to do any good.

957
00:56:25.880 --> 00:56:27.680
I already tried
talking to my men,

958
00:56:27.760 --> 00:56:29.760
but everything
about this land
has them spooked.

959
00:56:29.840 --> 00:56:34.520
[howling, moaning]

960
00:56:34.600 --> 00:56:36.920
That's the strangest creature
I've ever seen!

961
00:56:36.960 --> 00:56:40.080
[yowling, whining]

962
00:56:41.320 --> 00:56:42.640
Percy?

963
00:56:42.720 --> 00:56:44.960
[chittering]
[snarling, barking]

964
00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:46.480
Easy, Percy! Come here!

965
00:56:46.560 --> 00:56:47.760
Meeko, come back!

966
00:56:47.880 --> 00:56:50.640
You see what I mean?
Once two sides want to fight,
nothing can stop them.

967
00:56:50.760 --> 00:56:53.960
Come here, both of you!
It's all right.
He's a friend.

968
00:56:54.000 --> 00:56:55.400
Bad! Bad dog! Sit!
[barking]

969
00:56:55.440 --> 00:56:57.600
[squeaking]

970
00:56:57.640 --> 00:56:59.040
[Pocahontas]
What are you doing?
Meeko!

971
00:56:59.120 --> 00:57:00.600
[John]
Percy, get back here!

972
00:57:00.640 --> 00:57:02.280
What are you doing?
Stop that!

973
00:57:02.320 --> 00:57:04.120
All right,
that's enough!

974
00:57:04.200 --> 00:57:05.760
[whimpering]

975
00:57:09.800 --> 00:57:11.120
[whining]

976
00:57:11.200 --> 00:57:13.800
It's enough to make
your sap boil.

977
00:57:15.200 --> 00:57:19.600
Now then, there's something
I want to show you. Look!

978
00:57:23.640 --> 00:57:26.920
The ripples.
What about them?

979
00:57:27.000 --> 00:57:31.600
So small at first,
then look how they grow.

980
00:57:32.840 --> 00:57:35.600
But someone
has to start them.

981
00:57:35.680 --> 00:57:37.840
They're not going
to listen to us.

982
00:57:37.920 --> 00:57:42.160
Young man, sometimes
the right path is not
the easiest one.

983
00:57:42.200 --> 00:57:44.000
Don't you see?

984
00:57:44.080 --> 00:57:48.520
Only when the fighting stops
can you be together.

985
00:57:52.520 --> 00:57:55.000
All right.
Let's go talk
to your father.

986
00:58:00.280 --> 00:58:02.080
[purring]

987
00:58:02.160 --> 00:58:03.840
[squeaking]

988
00:58:27.120 --> 00:58:28.840
[war whooping]

989
00:58:28.880 --> 00:58:29.920
[gasping]

990
00:58:30.000 --> 00:58:31.200
[grunting]

991
00:58:31.280 --> 00:58:33.720
Kocoum, no!

992
00:58:33.760 --> 00:58:36.160
[straining]

993
00:58:40.080 --> 00:58:41.240
Kocoum!

994
00:58:44.880 --> 00:58:46.720
Leave him alone!

995
00:58:46.760 --> 00:58:48.720
[grunting, gasping]

996
00:58:49.640 --> 00:58:50.720
[straining, grunting]

997
00:59:02.680 --> 00:59:04.760
Kocoum, stop!

998
00:59:07.040 --> 00:59:09.600
Both eyes open.

999
00:59:09.680 --> 00:59:10.960
[blasting]
[groaning]

1000
00:59:11.040 --> 00:59:13.200
[gasping]

1001
00:59:17.800 --> 00:59:20.160
Thomas!
Is he...

1002
00:59:20.240 --> 00:59:22.120
You killed him.

1003
00:59:22.160 --> 00:59:24.120
I thought that...
Get away from him!

1004
00:59:24.160 --> 00:59:26.280
Pocahontas, it won't help!
He was only...

1005
00:59:26.360 --> 00:59:27.360
He killed him!

1006
00:59:28.960 --> 00:59:30.920
[man]
Get all the wagons...

1007
00:59:30.960 --> 00:59:34.600
Thomas, get out of here!
Get out of here!

1008
00:59:35.360 --> 00:59:37.120
[war whooping]
[whimpering]

1009
00:59:53.720 --> 00:59:57.280
[murmuring in Algonquian]

1010
01:00:09.160 --> 01:00:13.120
[chittering]
[whimpering]

1011
01:00:17.400 --> 01:00:20.360
[whining]
[purring]

1012
01:00:31.520 --> 01:00:34.680
[murmuring, wailing]

1013
01:00:34.760 --> 01:00:37.720
[crowd gasps, weeps]

1014
01:00:38.240 --> 01:00:39.800
Who did this?

1015
01:00:39.840 --> 01:00:41.880
Pocahontas was out
in the woods.

1016
01:00:41.960 --> 01:00:44.880
Kocoum went to find her
and this white man
attacked them.

1017
01:00:46.720 --> 01:00:51.840
Your weapons are strong,
but now our anger
is stronger.

1018
01:00:51.920 --> 01:00:54.520
At sunrise,
he'll be the first to die!

1019
01:00:54.600 --> 01:00:55.920
But, Father!

1020
01:00:56.000 --> 01:00:58.960
I told you to stay
in the village.

1021
01:00:59.040 --> 01:01:00.960
You disobeyed me.

1022
01:01:01.040 --> 01:01:02.920
You have shamed
your father!

1023
01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:04.800
I was only
trying to help.

1024
01:01:04.880 --> 01:01:08.880
Because of your foolishness,
Kocoum is dead!

1025
01:01:08.920 --> 01:01:10.760
Take him away!

1026
01:01:25.240 --> 01:01:27.440
Kocoum was just coming
to protect me.

1027
01:01:27.520 --> 01:01:31.440
Pocahontas...
I sent Kocoum after you.

1028
01:01:33.600 --> 01:01:35.720
I was worried about you.

1029
01:01:35.760 --> 01:01:37.960
I thought I was doing
the right thing.

1030
01:01:38.040 --> 01:01:40.960
All this happened
because of me.

1031
01:01:41.040 --> 01:01:44.080
And now I'll never see
John Smith again.

1032
01:01:46.240 --> 01:01:47.720
Come with me.

1033
01:01:49.520 --> 01:01:52.240
[tribal drums, chanting]

1034
01:01:52.640 --> 01:01:56.760
Pocahontas wants to look
into the eyes of the man
who killed Kocoum.

1035
01:01:59.280 --> 01:02:00.960
Be quick.

1036
01:02:19.280 --> 01:02:21.040
Pocahontas.

1037
01:02:23.440 --> 01:02:25.600
I'm so sorry.

1038
01:02:25.720 --> 01:02:27.080
For what? This?

1039
01:02:27.120 --> 01:02:29.440
I've gotten out of
worse scrapes than this.

1040
01:02:29.520 --> 01:02:31.160
Can't think of any
right now, but...

1041
01:02:31.240 --> 01:02:33.360
It would've been better
if we'd never met.

1042
01:02:33.440 --> 01:02:35.440
None of this
would've happened.

1043
01:02:35.480 --> 01:02:37.440
Pocahontas, look at me.

1044
01:02:38.560 --> 01:02:44.320
I'd rather die tomorrow
than live a hundred years
without knowing you.

1045
01:02:44.400 --> 01:02:45.480
Pocahontas.

1046
01:02:46.040 --> 01:02:47.480
I can't leave you.

1047
01:02:47.560 --> 01:02:49.160
You never will.

1048
01:02:49.200 --> 01:02:54.000
No matter what happens to me,
I'll always be with you.
Forever.

1049
01:03:07.400 --> 01:03:10.320
[Thomas] Help!
Somebody help! Help!

1050
01:03:10.400 --> 01:03:12.160
Help!
Easy, lad. What is it?

1051
01:03:12.200 --> 01:03:13.880
It's Smith!
They got him!

1052
01:03:13.960 --> 01:03:15.520
Who got him?
The savages!

1053
01:03:15.560 --> 01:03:18.040
Savages?
They captured him!
Dragged him off!

1054
01:03:18.120 --> 01:03:19.880
Where'd they take him?
They headed north.

1055
01:03:19.960 --> 01:03:21.000
[man]
How many were there?

1056
01:03:21.080 --> 01:03:22.120
[Thomas] I don't know.
At least a dozen.

1057
01:03:22.160 --> 01:03:24.320
[Ben] Filthy beasts!

1058
01:03:24.360 --> 01:03:28.280
It's perfect, Wiggins!
I couldn't have planned
this better myself.

1059
01:03:28.360 --> 01:03:31.320
The gold is
as good as mine.

1060
01:03:31.360 --> 01:03:34.200
We've got to save him!
He'd do the same
for any of us.

1061
01:03:34.240 --> 01:03:36.560
Thomas is right!
We've got to do something.

1062
01:03:36.640 --> 01:03:41.440
And so we shall.
I told you those savages
couldn't be trusted.

1063
01:03:41.520 --> 01:03:43.200
Smith tried to
befriend them,

1064
01:03:43.280 --> 01:03:44.880
and look what
they've done to him!

1065
01:03:44.920 --> 01:03:48.920
But now I say
it's time to rescue
our courageous comrade.

1066
01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:51.200
At daybreak, we attack!

1067
01:03:51.240 --> 01:03:52.560
[cheering]

1068
01:03:52.680 --> 01:03:56.080
<i>♪ What can you expect</i>
<i>from filthy little heathens? ♪</i>

1069
01:03:56.160 --> 01:03:59.280
<i>♪ Here's what you get</i>
<i>when races are diverse ♪</i>

1070
01:03:59.360 --> 01:04:01.160
<i>♪ Their skin's</i>
<i>a hellish red ♪</i>

1071
01:04:01.200 --> 01:04:02.880
<i>♪ They're only good</i>
<i>when dead ♪</i>

1072
01:04:02.920 --> 01:04:05.360
<i>♪ They're vermin</i>
<i>as I said and worse ♪</i>

1073
01:04:05.400 --> 01:04:08.280
<i>♪ They're savages, savages ♪</i>

1074
01:04:08.360 --> 01:04:11.400
<i>♪ Barely even human ♪</i>
<i>♪ Savages, savages ♪</i>

1075
01:04:11.480 --> 01:04:13.240
<i>♪ Drive them</i>
<i>from our shore! ♪</i>

1076
01:04:13.280 --> 01:04:14.920
<i>♪ They're not like</i>
<i>you and me ♪</i>

1077
01:04:15.040 --> 01:04:16.560
<i>♪ Which means</i>
<i>they must be evil ♪</i>

1078
01:04:16.640 --> 01:04:19.480
<i>♪ We must sound</i>
<i>the drums of war ♪</i>

1079
01:04:19.560 --> 01:04:21.560
<i>♪ They're savages, savages ♪</i>

1080
01:04:21.640 --> 01:04:23.480
<i>♪ Dirty, shrieking devils ♪</i>

1081
01:04:23.560 --> 01:04:27.400
<i>♪ Now we sound</i>
<i>the drums of war ♪</i>

1082
01:04:32.120 --> 01:04:33.920
<i>♪ This is what we feared ♪</i>

1083
01:04:33.960 --> 01:04:35.600
<i>♪ The paleface is a demon ♪</i>

1084
01:04:35.680 --> 01:04:38.640
<i>♪ The only thing</i>
<i>they feel at all is greed ♪</i>

1085
01:04:38.720 --> 01:04:40.520
<i>♪ Beneath that milky hide ♪</i>

1086
01:04:40.600 --> 01:04:42.240
<i>♪ There's emptiness inside ♪</i>

1087
01:04:42.320 --> 01:04:45.280
<i>♪ I wonder if</i>
<i>they even bleed ♪</i>

1088
01:04:45.280 --> 01:04:47.520
<i>♪ They're savages, savages ♪</i>

1089
01:04:47.600 --> 01:04:49.280
<i>♪ Barely even human ♪</i>

1090
01:04:49.320 --> 01:04:51.040
<i>♪ Savages, savages ♪</i>

1091
01:04:51.080 --> 01:04:52.320
<i>♪ Killers at the core ♪</i>

1092
01:04:52.400 --> 01:04:54.200
<i>♪ They're different from us ♪</i>

1093
01:04:54.280 --> 01:04:56.280
<i>♪ Which means</i>
<i>they can't be trusted ♪</i>

1094
01:04:56.320 --> 01:04:59.240
<i>♪ We must sound</i>
<i>the drums of war ♪</i>

1095
01:04:59.280 --> 01:05:01.280
<i>♪ They're savages, savages ♪</i>

1096
01:05:01.320 --> 01:05:03.080
<i>♪ First we deal</i>
<i>with this one ♪</i>

1097
01:05:03.120 --> 01:05:04.640
<i>♪ Then we sound</i>
<i>the drums of war ♪</i>

1098
01:05:04.720 --> 01:05:06.280
<i>♪ Savages, savages ♪</i>

1099
01:05:06.320 --> 01:05:08.120
Let's go get a few, men!

1100
01:05:08.200 --> 01:05:09.960
<i>♪ Savages, savages ♪</i>

1101
01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:11.520
<i>♪ Now it's up to you, men! ♪</i>

1102
01:05:11.600 --> 01:05:13.320
<i>♪ Savages ♪</i>
<i>♪ Savages ♪</i>

1103
01:05:13.400 --> 01:05:15.120
<i>♪ Barely even human ♪</i>

1104
01:05:15.200 --> 01:05:18.560
<i>♪ Now we sound the drums ♪</i>

1105
01:05:18.640 --> 01:05:23.640
<i>♪ Of war ♪♪</i>

1106
01:05:30.440 --> 01:05:33.320
They're going to
kill him at sunrise,
Grandmother Willow.

1107
01:05:33.400 --> 01:05:35.000
You have to stop them.

1108
01:05:35.120 --> 01:05:36.600
I can't.

1109
01:05:36.640 --> 01:05:38.560
Child,
remember your dream.

1110
01:05:38.640 --> 01:05:42.480
I was wrong,
Grandmother Willow.
I followed the wrong path.

1111
01:05:42.520 --> 01:05:44.680
I feel so lost.

1112
01:05:44.760 --> 01:05:46.920
[chittering]

1113
01:05:52.480 --> 01:05:53.800
[whining]

1114
01:05:55.040 --> 01:05:56.560
[purring]

1115
01:06:02.320 --> 01:06:04.040
The compass.

1116
01:06:12.400 --> 01:06:14.320
The spinning arrow.

1117
01:06:14.360 --> 01:06:16.560
It's the arrow
from your dream!

1118
01:06:16.640 --> 01:06:19.760
I was right.
It was pointing to him!

1119
01:06:26.680 --> 01:06:29.360
Sunrise.
It's not too late, child!

1120
01:06:29.400 --> 01:06:32.960
Let the spirits
of the earth guide you!

1121
01:06:34.480 --> 01:06:39.280
You know your path, child.
Now follow it!

1122
01:06:42.480 --> 01:06:44.200
<i>♪ This will be the day ♪</i>

1123
01:06:44.280 --> 01:06:47.160
Let's go, men!

1124
01:06:47.200 --> 01:06:49.760
<i>♪ This will be the morning ♪</i>

1125
01:06:49.840 --> 01:06:52.480
Bring out the prisoner!

1126
01:06:52.560 --> 01:06:54.360
<i>♪ We will see them</i>
<i>dying in the dust ♪</i>

1127
01:06:54.400 --> 01:06:55.640
<i>♪ I don't know</i>
<i>what I can do ♪</i>

1128
01:06:55.720 --> 01:06:57.560
<i>♪ Still I know</i>
<i>I've got to try ♪</i>

1129
01:06:57.640 --> 01:06:59.360
<i>♪ Now we make them pay ♪</i>

1130
01:06:59.400 --> 01:07:01.040
<i>♪ Eagle,</i>
<i>help my feet to fly ♪</i>

1131
01:07:01.160 --> 01:07:02.520
<i>♪ Now, without a warning ♪</i>

1132
01:07:02.560 --> 01:07:04.360
<i>♪ Mountain,</i>
<i>help my heart be great ♪</i>

1133
01:07:04.400 --> 01:07:06.200
<i>♪ Now we leave them</i>
<i>blood and bone and rust ♪</i>

1134
01:07:06.240 --> 01:07:09.760
<i>♪ Spirits of</i>
<i>the earth and sky ♪</i>
<i>♪ It's them or us ♪</i>

1135
01:07:09.840 --> 01:07:12.480
<i>♪ Please don't let it</i>
<i>be too late ♪</i>

1136
01:07:12.560 --> 01:07:15.080
<i>♪ They're a bunch of</i>
<i>filthy, stinking savages ♪</i>

1137
01:07:15.120 --> 01:07:16.320
<i>♪ Savages ♪</i>
<i>♪ Demons ♪</i>

1138
01:07:16.400 --> 01:07:17.480
<i>♪ Devils ♪</i>
Kill them!

1139
01:07:17.560 --> 01:07:19.080
<i>♪ Savages ♪</i>
<i>♪ Savages ♪</i>

1140
01:07:19.160 --> 01:07:20.480
What are we
waiting for?

1141
01:07:20.560 --> 01:07:22.360
<i>♪ Destroy their evil race ♪</i>

1142
01:07:22.400 --> 01:07:24.240
<i>♪ Until there's not</i>
<i>a trace left ♪</i>

1143
01:07:24.280 --> 01:07:31.120
<i>♪ How loud are</i>
<i>the drums of war? ♪</i>

1144
01:07:31.200 --> 01:07:34.240
<i>♪ Now we see what comes</i>
<i>of trying to be chums ♪</i>

1145
01:07:34.360 --> 01:07:39.640
<i>♪ Is the death of all I love</i>
<i>carried in the drumming of ♪</i>

1146
01:07:39.720 --> 01:07:40.880
<i>♪ War ♪♪</i>
No!

1147
01:07:45.360 --> 01:07:48.400
If you kill him,
you'll have to kill me too.

1148
01:07:48.440 --> 01:07:50.680
Daughter, stand back.

1149
01:07:50.760 --> 01:07:54.720
I won't!
I love him, Father.

1150
01:08:00.880 --> 01:08:02.760
Look around you.

1151
01:08:02.800 --> 01:08:05.920
This is where the path
of hatred has brought us.

1152
01:08:08.840 --> 01:08:11.360
This is the path
I choose, Father.

1153
01:08:11.440 --> 01:08:12.800
What will yours be?

1154
01:08:22.080 --> 01:08:25.160
[wind whistling]

1155
01:08:47.440 --> 01:08:51.600
My daughter speaks
with a wisdom
beyond her years.

1156
01:08:51.680 --> 01:08:54.840
We have all come here
with anger in our hearts,

1157
01:08:54.920 --> 01:08:58.000
but she comes with
courage and understanding.

1158
01:08:59.200 --> 01:09:03.000
From this day forward,
if there is to be
more killing,

1159
01:09:03.120 --> 01:09:05.120
it will not
start with me.

1160
01:09:08.840 --> 01:09:09.840
Release him.

1161
01:09:28.400 --> 01:09:30.080
Now is our chance! Fire!

1162
01:09:30.160 --> 01:09:32.040
[Thomas] No.
What?

1163
01:09:32.120 --> 01:09:34.840
They let him go!
They don't want to fight!

1164
01:09:34.880 --> 01:09:38.040
It's a trick,
don't you see? Fire!

1165
01:09:43.120 --> 01:09:44.800
Fine!
I'll settle this myself.

1166
01:09:47.480 --> 01:09:48.520
No!

1167
01:09:49.840 --> 01:09:50.960
John!

1168
01:09:56.920 --> 01:09:58.000
You shot him!

1169
01:09:58.080 --> 01:10:01.760
He stepped right into it!
It's his own fault!

1170
01:10:01.800 --> 01:10:03.000
[Ben] Smith was
right all along.

1171
01:10:03.080 --> 01:10:04.440
[man] We never should've
listened to you.

1172
01:10:04.520 --> 01:10:06.800
[Ben] Get the gun!
Traitors!

1173
01:10:06.880 --> 01:10:08.800
Unhand me, I say.
How dare you!

1174
01:10:08.880 --> 01:10:10.760
Put him in chains!

1175
01:10:10.800 --> 01:10:13.440
I'll see you all
hanged for this!

1176
01:10:13.440 --> 01:10:15.600
And gag him as well!
[grunting, yelling]

1177
01:10:21.000 --> 01:10:23.920
[seagulls cry]

1178
01:10:27.280 --> 01:10:28.920
Is he going to make it,
Thomas?

1179
01:10:29.040 --> 01:10:30.880
The sooner he gets
to England, the better.

1180
01:10:30.920 --> 01:10:32.760
Let's hope the wind
is with him.

1181
01:10:32.800 --> 01:10:35.160
Is the ship ready yet?
Any minute now.

1182
01:10:35.240 --> 01:10:37.960
Just loading the
last bit of cargo.

1183
01:10:38.040 --> 01:10:39.520
[muffled screaming]

1184
01:10:42.000 --> 01:10:45.760
Untie me at once!
I'll have your head
for this!

1185
01:10:45.800 --> 01:10:48.880
[sniffling] And he came
so highly recommended.

1186
01:10:48.960 --> 01:10:50.280
[sighing]

1187
01:10:57.800 --> 01:10:59.640
The ship's almost ready.

1188
01:10:59.720 --> 01:11:02.480
We'd better get you on board.
We'll lose the tide.

1189
01:11:02.560 --> 01:11:05.840
No, not yet.
She said she'd be here.

1190
01:11:06.680 --> 01:11:07.800
Look.

1191
01:11:34.560 --> 01:11:36.840
Going back is
his only chance.

1192
01:11:36.880 --> 01:11:39.280
He'll die
if he stays here.

1193
01:11:47.880 --> 01:11:49.680
Here.

1194
01:11:49.760 --> 01:11:52.120
It's from
Grandmother Willow's bark.

1195
01:11:52.200 --> 01:11:54.120
It'll help with the pain.

1196
01:11:54.200 --> 01:11:57.560
What pain? I've had
worse pain than this.

1197
01:11:59.040 --> 01:12:01.080
Can't think of
any right now, but...

1198
01:12:07.360 --> 01:12:10.880
You are always welcome
among our people.

1199
01:12:10.920 --> 01:12:12.920
Thank you, my brother.

1200
01:12:16.040 --> 01:12:19.040
I thought you
didn't like strangers.
[chirps]

1201
01:12:27.200 --> 01:12:29.240
My mother's necklace.

1202
01:12:31.880 --> 01:12:34.600
[whimpering]
See ya, Percy.

1203
01:12:36.640 --> 01:12:37.840
[sneezing]

1204
01:12:51.800 --> 01:12:53.240
Come with me?

1205
01:12:57.840 --> 01:13:00.200
You must choose
your own path.

1206
01:13:15.840 --> 01:13:17.760
I'm needed here.

1207
01:13:19.120 --> 01:13:21.840
Then... I'll stay with you.

1208
01:13:21.960 --> 01:13:24.880
No. You have to go back.

1209
01:13:24.960 --> 01:13:26.280
But I can't leave you.

1210
01:13:26.360 --> 01:13:27.760
You never will.

1211
01:13:27.880 --> 01:13:32.000
No matter what happens,
I'll always be with you...

1212
01:13:33.080 --> 01:13:34.440
...forever.

1213
01:14:01.520 --> 01:14:04.000
Good luck, lad.
Godspeed, John.

1214
01:14:10.440 --> 01:14:12.840
[man] The crew a-ready?
[man 2] Aye, sir!

1215
01:14:12.920 --> 01:14:14.840
Set the mainsails.

1216
01:14:17.320 --> 01:14:19.440
[man] Weigh anchor!

1217
01:14:21.000 --> 01:14:22.520
[man 2] Let go
of the topgallants!

1218
01:14:33.920 --> 01:14:36.200
[panting]

1219
01:14:47.040 --> 01:14:50.480
[wind singing]

